# Git Commit Message Format

Use **Conventional Commits** for clear history and tooling (changelogs, semantic versioning).

## Format

```
type(scope): <subject>

[optional body]

[optional footer]
```

**subject**: One line, imperative mood, <64 characters. No period at end.
**body** (optional): Wrap at 72 chars. Explain "what" and "why", not "how".
**footer** (optional): e.g. `Fixes #123`, `BREAKING CHANGE:`.

## Types

| Type | Use For |
|------|---------|
| feat | New feature |
| fix | Bug fix |
| docs | Documentation only |
| style | Formatting, semicolons (no code change) |
| refactor | Code change that neither fixes bug nor adds feature |
| test | Adding or updating tests |
| chore | Build, tooling, dependencies, config |

**scope** (optional): Short noun: `auth`, `packages`, `warehouses`, `api`, `deps`. Omit if unclear.

## Examples

**Good:**
```
feat(packages): add warehouse filter dropdown
fix: correct localStorage key for auth token
docs: update README with run instructions
chore(deps): add chart.js

```

**Avoid:**
```
Fixed stuff
WIP
updated code
```

When suggesting or writing commit messages, use this format.
